body:
> @TheDonsky That sounds like it might be a separate bug. If it's still happening, please open an issue for it. I'll need the version of GLFW and Windows and if possible the controller model and if it's wired or not.

Controller is a regular Xbox 360 wireless controller, with the standard receiver, Microsoft sold;
Windows: Build 19043.1052 (Windows 10 Home);
GLFW: 3.3.2 

Exact "symptoms" are as follows:
I have a functioning input, as long as the joystick is already connected when I first call glfwInit(); 
If I disconnect the controller, glfwSetJoystickCallback correctly reports the event and, naturally, my input module goes silent for the device. 
Problem starts, when I reconnect the controller or simply connect it after glfwInit: glfwSetJoystickCallback reports nothing and glfwJoystickPresent/glfwGetGamepadState calls do not give me anything useful any more.

Project is not "tied" to the above version, so if it's likely fixed in the latter version, I can test with the new build without too many complications; Also, I've tested the same on my linux(Ubuntu) machine and the same code works perfectly fine there (same version). So, this makes it a Windows-only issue for me

For additional insights, feel free to look at the exact code, in case it helps: 
[https://github.com/TheDonsky/Jimara/blob/main/__Source__/Jimara/OS/Window/GLFW/GLFW_Window.cpp](url) (line 34 for glfwSetJoystickCallback);
[https://github.com/TheDonsky/Jimara/blob/main/__Source__/Jimara/OS/Window/GLFW/GLFW_Input.cpp](url) (line 359 onward for gamepad state);
Behavior can be observed from any test case, that creates a window and displays some amount of 3d graphics (for example, [https://github.com/TheDonsky/Jimara/blob/main/__Source__/Jimara-Tests/Components/MeshRendererTest.cpp](url) but I think you probably won't need to build it, but anyway...)
